<p>The <b>Zohar</b> (<a href="/wiki/Hebrew_language" title="Hebrew language">Hebrew</a>: <span dir="rtl" style="font-family:&quot;SBL Hebrew&quot;, david, narkisim, &quot;Microsoft Sans Serif&quot;; font-size:125%;" lang="he" xml:lang="he">זֹהַר</span>‎, lit <i>Splendor</i> or <i>Radiance</i>) is widely considered the most important work of <a href="/wiki/Kabbalah" title="Kabbalah">Kabbalah</a>, or Jewish mysticism. It is a mystical commentary on the <a href="/wiki/Torah" title="Torah">Torah</a> (the five books of <a href="/wiki/Moses" title="Moses">Moses</a>), written in medieval <a href="/wiki/Aramaic_language" title="Aramaic language">Aramaic</a>. It contains a mystical discussion of the nature of <a href="/wiki/Names_of_God_in_Judaism" title="Names of God in Judaism">God</a>, the origin and structure of the universe, the nature of <a href="/wiki/Soul" title="Soul">souls</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sin" title="Sin">sin</a>, redemption, good and evil, and the relationship between God and man.</p>
<p>The Zohar is not one book, but a group of books; these books include scriptural interpretations as well as material on <a href="/wiki/Theosophy_(history_of_philosophy)" title="Theosophy (history of philosophy)">theosophic</a> theology, mythical <a href="/wiki/Cosmogony" title="Cosmogony">cosmogony</a>, and mystical psychology.</p>
